<Project slug="tprm-framework">
  <p class="lead">
    Third-party risk is where most security programmes leak. A bank can have
    perfect internal controls and still suffer a major breach because a vendor
    handling customer data is compromised.
  </p>

  <h2>The problem I wanted to solve</h2>
  <p>
    After MAS heightened its focus on outsourcing risk, Singapore FSI hiring
    managers specifically test TPRM knowledge in interviews. Most candidates have
    a risk register, but very few have produced actual TPRM artefacts. This
    project deliberately fills that portfolio gap.
  </p>

  <h2>How I approached it</h2>

  <h3>Policy first</h3>
  <p>
    Policy establishes the governance framework everything else operates within.
    The TPRM policy anchors to <span class="cite">MAS TRM §9</span> and the MAS
    Outsourcing Guidelines as the regulatory basis, with
    <span class="cite">ISO 27001 A.5.19–A.5.22</span> providing international
    standards alignment. It's structured in five sections — purpose and scope,
    vendor tiering, the five-phase vendor lifecycle, roles and responsibilities,
    and regulatory references — with a document control table showing version
    history, approval authority and review cadence. This is what an operational
    policy looks like, not a templated example.
  </p>

  <h3>Tiering by materiality</h3>
  <p>
    <span class="cite">MAS TRM §9.2.1</span> requires materiality assessment —
    different vendors get different scrutiny based on how critical they are and how
    sensitive the data they access. I built a three-tier scheme:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tier 1</strong> — restricted data access or core platform dependency: annual security assessment, full questionnaire, SOC 2 review, contractual right-to-audit.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 2</strong> — confidential data access: annual questionnaire, certificate review, contractual security clauses.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 3</strong> — productivity tools, no sensitive data: standard contract review, bi-annual cadence.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>A realistic inventory</h3>
  <p>
    I built an inventory of 12 fictional vendors representative of a real
    Singapore fintech — AWS for cloud, Stripe for payments, Okta for identity,
    GitHub Enterprise for code, plus the usual SaaS tail. Each is classified by
    tier, with annual spend in SGD, renewal date, certification status and a named
    risk owner.
  </p>

  <h3>The questionnaire</h3>
  <p>
    The Vendor Risk Assessment Questionnaire is the operational vehicle of the
    framework — 38 questions across seven domains: governance, information
    security and data protection, compliance and certifications, business
    continuity, incident response and breach notification, sub-contractors and
    supply chain, and right to audit. Each section opens with a paragraph
    explaining why the questions matter, so vendors understand the rationale rather
    than feeling interrogated. Metadata fields at the start, attestation page with
    signatures at the end.
  </p>

  <h3>Scoring that differentiates</h3>
  <p>
    The scoring methodology applies domain weightings — information security and
    data protection at 25%, the others at 10–15% each. Each question scores 1–5
    with documented rationale per level. The weighted average produces a final
    score with an auto-calculated decision: Approve, Approve with Conditions,
    Conditional/Remediate or Reject.
  </p>
  <div class="callout">
    <span class="section-mark">The real test</span>
    <p>
      Does it differentiate?
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>DataPulse Analytics</strong> (Tier 1, fraud
      detection — strong SOC 2 Type II, ISO 27001 certified) scores ~4.7 and earns
      "Approve".
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>SwiftDesk Solutions</strong> (Tier 2, support — solid SOC 2
      but no ISO 27001, weaker BCP) scores ~3.0 and earns "Approve with Conditions".
    </p>
    <p>
      The deliberate spread proves the methodology produces different outcomes for
      different vendor profiles — which is the whole point.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>What I produced</h2>
  <p>
    A five-sheet Excel workbook containing the methodology, vendor inventory,
    scoring matrix, dashboard and cover. A Vendor Risk Assessment Questionnaire in
    Word with seven sections and 38 questions. And a formal TPRM policy in Word
    covering scope, tiering, lifecycle phases, roles and regulatory references.
  </p>

  <h2>What this demonstrates</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>I understand Singapore's regulatory expectations for vendor risk.</li>
    <li>I can operationalise TPRM, not just describe it.</li>
    <li>I think across the full vendor lifecycle — due diligence, contracting, onboarding, monitoring, termination.</li>
    <li>The policy I wrote would survive MAS inspection, and the scoring actually differentiates vendors.</li>
  </ul>
</Project>
